"Acute Pericarditis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s17_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f0e1b1",
"children":[
"Acute pericarditis is diagnosed clinically by the presence of at least two of four criteria:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"6e2f89",
"children":[
"chest pain typical for pericarditis"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"8f9c03",
"children":[
"pericardial friction rub (classically three phases)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"9b4ce4",
"children":[
"new ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"electrocardiogram",
"children":[
"ECG"
]
},
" changes"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"ef4154",
"children":[
"new pericardial effusion"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"51af6a",
"children":[
"Chest pain is sharp, severe, and positional; is worse in the supine position; and improves with sitting up and leaning forward."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_cv_s17_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"heading",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
"Don't Be Tricked"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"class":"tricked",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"f4371f",
"children":[
"Cardiac enzyme values may be slightly elevated in patients with pericarditis (myopericarditis)."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"82be0d",
"children":[
"Absence of a pericardial effusion on echocardiography does not rule out pericarditis."
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s17_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"e5b923",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"alert",
"children":[
"First-line treatment is colchicine plus aspirin (preferred after ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"myocardial infarction",
"children":[
"MI"
]
},
") or an NSAID."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"9eeee9",
"children":[
"Add glucocorticoids to first-line treatment for pericarditis that is:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"1cba2a",
"children":[
"recurrent (second or third recurrence), incessant (>4 to 6 weeks), chronic (>3 months)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"7992b2",
"children":[
"uremic, unresponsive to dialysis"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"17325a",
"children":[
"autoimmune"
]
},
" "
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_cv_s17_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"cea849",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 57-year-old man has a 2-day history of chest pain that worsens when he lies flat. Cardiac examination shows a three-component friction rub."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"8757d2",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose pericarditis. Look for diffuse ST-segment elevation and PR-segment depression. Ignore slight elevation of cardiac troponin tempting you to answer “acute MI.”"
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_cv_f22"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
}
]
},
